title: Project Overview
text: SKTools R package developed Samuel Kaminsky designed facilitate data import, cleaning, analysis. provides collection utility functions streamline common tasks working data frames R.

title: Project Overview
text: Data Import/Export: Functions like read_excel_all read.xlsx.handling multiple sheets/files. Descriptive Statistics: Tools like descriptives frequencies quick data summarization. Data Manipulation: Helpers like append_2_prepend distinct_2col. Integration: Designed work well tidyverse ecosystem.

title: Project Overview
text: Language: R Package Structure: Standard R package structure (R/ source, man/ docs, tests/ unit tests). Dependencies: Heavy reliance tidyverse (dplyr, purrr, tidyr, readr), plus openxlsx, psych, others listed DESCRIPTION.

title: Project Overview
text: Tidyverse Style: code heavily utilizes pipe operator (%>%) dplyr verbs. Explicit Namespacing: Functions packages generally called namespace (e.g., dplyr::mutate, stats::sd) rather relying library() calls within functions. best practice package development. Pronouns: Usage .data pronoun inside dplyr verbs avoid ambiguity (e.g., .data$value).

title: Project Overview
text: Roxygen2: exported functions documented using Roxygen2 comments (#') immediately preceding function definition. Parameters: @param, @return, @export, @description tags standard.

text: Git: project version-controlled Git. CI/CD: Configuration exists GitHub Actions (.github/workflows).

title: Calculate Adverse Impact Metrics — calculate_ai
text: df Dataframe passrate information. Must include columns grouping interest columns logicals indicating success stage groupings Character vector names column containing grouping variables (e.g, race, gender, etc.) stage1 Unquoted column name column indicating whether row counted calculations (.e., denominator). Column must logical. stage2 Unquoted column name column indicating whether row counted 'Pass' calculations (.e., numerator). Column must logical. n_min Minimum n count group included calculation prop_min Minimum percentage group included calculation only_max calculate adverse impact using group highest selection ratio denominator correct logical indicating whether Yates' continuity correction applied possible.

title: Calculate Adverse Impact Metrics — calculate_ai
text: List two data frames. first includes selection ratios,   second includes adverse impact calculation selection_ratio Dataframe selection ratios adverse_impact Dataframe adverse impact metrics, including adverse impact ratio, Cohen's H, Z score test two proportions, Pearson's chi-squared test proportions, Fisher's exact

title: Calculate Adverse Impact Metrics — calculate_ai
text: Calculates selection ratios adverse impact using Fisher's Exact   Test, Z-test two proportions, Chi-Squared test.

title: Calculate Adverse Impact Metrics — calculate_ai
code: df <- tibble::tibble(   gender = c(rep("Male", 10), rep("Female", 10)),   applied = c(rep(TRUE, 10), rep(TRUE, 10)),   hired = c(rep(TRUE, 5), rep(FALSE, 5), rep(TRUE, 8), rep(FALSE, 2)) ) calculate_ai(df, groupings = "gender", stage1 = applied, stage2 = hired) #> Warning: There were 2 warnings in `dplyr::mutate()`. #> The first warning was: #> ℹ In argument: `chi = #>   list(broom::tidy(stats::prop.test(as.matrix(.data$conting), correct = #>   correct)))`. #> ℹ In row 1. #> Caused by warning in `stats::prop.test()`: #> ! Chi-squared approximation may be incorrect #> ℹ Run `dplyr::last_dplyr_warnings()` to see the 1 remaining warning. #> $selection_ratio #> # A tibble: 2 × 5 #>   Grouping Group  applied_n hired_n    SR #>   <chr>    <chr>      <int>   <int> <dbl> #> 1 gender   Female        10       8   0.8 #> 2 gender   Male          10       5   0.5 #>  #> $adverse_impact #> # A tibble: 2 × 10 #>   Grouping Numerator Denominator ai_ratio      H     Z   chi p_value_chi #>   <chr>    <chr>     <chr>          <dbl>  <dbl> <dbl> <dbl>       <dbl> #> 1 gender   Female    Male           1.6   -0.644 -1.41 0.879       0.348 #> 2 gender   Male      Female         0.625  0.644  1.41 0.879       0.348 #> # ℹ 2 more variables: odds_ratio <dbl>, p_value_fisher <dbl> #>
